                  <additions>
                  <list>
                    <item xml:id="a1">
                    <locus target="#iiv(erso)" facs="003"/>
                    <desc type="CalendaricNote">
                    <title type="complete" ref="LIT6011FeastsList"/>, and some other holidays.
                    At the top is a note which says: <q>The painter of this illumination is Wäldä Mika’el</q>
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a2">
                    <locus target="#160r #160v" facs="162 163"/>
                    <desc type="Asmat">Asmat prayer against hail,
                    Incipit: <foreign xml:lang="gez">ጸሎተ: በረድ: ደፍፍልዮን: ለአፌን: ጡጠርዮን: ቀራድድዮን: ድልጣኂን:<gap reason="omitted"/>አመሐልኩከ: አማኅፀንኩከ: አንተ: መልአከ: በረድ: ሞርሬዎን: ከመ: ኢታውርድ: በረድ: እምሰማይ:<gap reason="omitted"/></foreign>
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a3">
                    <locus target="#176v #177r" facs="179 179"> f. 176v, 177r, top margin</locus>
                    <desc type="Asmat">
                    Asmat prayer against physical and spiritual disease, in a later, crude hand
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a4">
                    <locus target="#178r" facs="180"> f. 178r, column 2 and bottom</locus>
                    <desc type="Asmat">
                    Asmat prayer for spiritual release from chains, in a later hand
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e1">
                    <locus target="#ir(ecto) #iv(erso) #iir(ecto) #179r #179v" facs="001 002 181 182"/>
                    <desc>
                    blank
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a5">
                    <locus target="#2r #2v #3v #4r #5r" facs="004 005 006 007"/>
                    <desc>
                    At the beginning of some psalms there is a healing prescription added in a later hand.
                    e.g.,
                    <locus target="#1a" facs="003"/> <q>“Oracle for pregnancy; ‘the leaf does not wither;’”</q>,  <q>“For enemy, [recite] ‘why do the nations rage?’”</q>,
                    <locus target="#2r" facs="003"/> <q>“For enemies, [recite] ‘How my enemies multiply’”</q>,
                    <locus target="#2v" facs="004"/> <q>“When I call, ‘your enemies will scatter’”</q>,
                    <locus target="#3v" facs="005"/> <q>“‘O Lord, in your anger’ recite with wine and with vineger and with oil”</q>,
                    <locus target="#4r" facs="005"/> <q>“if a woman is hated by her husband, anoint her organs with oil and recite”</q>,
                    <locus target="#5r" facs="006"/> <q>“recite for the love of the people, and anoint with oil.”</q>
                    Veronika Six (“A Psalter from Tübingen: Although Inconspicuous the Text, Neverthless a Treasure for Manuscriptology,” Aethiopica 13 [2010] 163–75), describes this phenomenon in a Psalter in the University of Tübingen; and see the comments in Bogdan Burtea’s entry on “Magic Literature” in EA (III:638–40)
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e2">
                    <locus target="#70r" facs="072"/>
                    <desc>
                    A small red and black cross is written in the margin to mark the midpoint of the <ref type="work" corresp="LIT2000Mazmur"/>
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a6">
                    <desc type="PurchaseNote">
                    A piece of lined paper was in the book.  On it, in Tǝgrǝñña, was a transaction of the purchase of sheep
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a7">
                    <desc type="Letter">
                    A second piece of lined paper in the book contained a letter
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e3">
                    <locus target="#8 #16 #53 #63 #76 #85 #92 #107 #130" facs="010 018 055 065 078 087 094 109 132"/>
                    <desc>
                    red yarn is sewn into the fore edge to mark content as navigation system
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e4">
                    <desc>
                    Numbered quires: quires 1–16
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e5">
                    <locus target="#7v #11r #43v #46r #47r" facs="010 013 046 048 049"/>
                    <desc>etc., words of text are written interlinearly</desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e6">
                    <locus target="#28r #54r #88r #88v #107v" facs="030 056 090 091 110"/>
                    <desc>etc., lines of text are written interlinearly</desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e7">
                    <locus target="#15v #22r #23v #26v" facs="018 024 026 029"/>
                    <desc>etc., text has been removed</desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e8">
                    <desc>
                    The scribe regularly has to complete a line of text on another line. Much of the problem is addressed through the selection of an appropriate aspect ratio for the codex combined with an appropriate script size. But, where the line of text is still too long, the scribe reduces the font size at the end of lines to avoid having to go onto the next line (throughout)
                    </desc>
                    </item>
